Class SingleList<T extends Comparable<T>>

java.lang.Object
cp213.SingleLink<T>
cp213.SingleList<T>
Type Parameters:
T - the SingleNode data type
All Implemented Interfaces:
Iterable<T>
public class SingleList<T extends Comparable<T>> extends SingleLink<T>
A single linked list structure of T objects. Extends the SingleLink class.

    • append

      Parameters:

    • clean

      public void clean()
      Removes duplicates from this. The list contains one and only one of each object formerly present in this. The first occurrence of each object is preserved.

    • combine

      public void combine(SingleList<T> left, SingleList<T> right)
      Combines the contents of left and right into this. Moves nodes only - does not refer to data in any way, or call the high-level methods insert or remove. left and right are empty when done. Nodes are moved alternately from left and right into this. this may be empty. May call any appropriate SingleLink helper methods available. left and right are not necessarily the same length.
      Parameters:
      left - the first SingleList to extract nodes from
      right - the second SingleList to extract nodes from

    • insert

      public void insert(int i, T datum)
      Inserts object into this at index i. If i greater than the length of this, append data to the rear of this.
      Parameters:
      i - The index to insert the new data at.
      datum - The new object to insert into this SingleList.

    • intersection

      public void intersection(SingleList<T> left, SingleList<T> right)
      Creates an intersection of left and right into this. Copies data to this. left and right are unchanged. Values from left are copied in order first, then objects from right are copied in order.

      In an intersection, data copied to this must appear in both left and right.

      Parameters:
      left - the first SingleList to create an intersection from
      right - the second SingleList to create an intersection from

    • split

      public void split(SingleList<T> left, SingleList<T> right)
      Splits the contents of this into left and right. Moves nodes only - does not move data or call high-level methods. this is empty when done.The first half of this is moved to left, and the last half of this is moved to right. If the resulting lengths are not the same, left should have one more object than right. Order is preserved. left and right may already contain data.
      Parameters:
      left - the first SingleList to move nodes to
      right - the second SingleList to move nodes to

    • splitAlternate

      public void splitAlternate(SingleList<T> left, SingleList<T> right)
      Splits the contents of this into left and right. Moves nodes only - does not move data or call the high-level methods insert or remove. this is empty when done. Nodes are moved alternately from this to the rear of left and right. left and right may already contain data.

      This is the opposite of the combine method.

      Parameters:
      left - the first SingleList to move nodes to
      right - the second SingleList to move nodes to

    • union

      public void union(SingleList<T> left, SingleList<T> right)
      Creates an union of left and right into this. Copies data to this. left and right are unchanged. Values from left are copied in order first, then objects from right are copied in order.

      In an intersection, data copied to this must appear in one or both of left and right.

      Parameters:
      left - the first SingleList to create an union from
      right - the second SingleList to create an union from
